        Official Singles Chart on 16/12/2016

        16 December 2016 - 22 December 2016

        The Official UK Singles Chart reflects the UK’s biggest songs of the week, based on audio and video streams, downloads, CDs and vinyl, compiled by the Official Charts Company. The UK Top 40 is broadcast on BBC Radio 1 and MTV, the Top 100 is published exclusively on OfficialCharts.com. View the biggest songs of 2024 so far.

        23rd December 2016

        Vote score

        "Rockabye" by Clean Bandit (feat Anne-Marie & Sean Paul) is this year's Official UK Charts Christmas number 1. This is the first Christmas number 1 single for all the artists on the song. Clean Bandit's previous number one single, "Rather Be" was released on January 17, 2014, and spent four weeks at number 1 (from January 20, 2014- February 17, 2014). Sean Paul featured on the remix of "Breathe" by Blu Cantrell, which topped the charts for four weeks in August, 2003. Sean Paul also featured on "What About Us" by The Saturdays which debuted at number 1 in March, 2013. "Rockabye" is Anne-Marie's first ever Official UK Charts number 1.

        "Human" by Rag'n'Bone Man is at number 2 this week. It's refreshing to have a "real song" with honest lyrics performing so well in a time when corporate pop music is dominating.

        "Glad All Over" by The Dave Clark Five reached number one on iTunes in the United Kingdom on December 20, 2016 and as a result is at number 31 on the UK Singles Charts. It was originally released on November 15, 1963.

        According to this:

        "When the Official Chart Company first started counting streaming in 2014, the number of streams delivered per week was 275 million. That figure has now swollen to 990 million, and is expected to pass 1 billion in the first weeks of next year."

        An incredible rise in streaming. The technology - superfast broadband/fibre optic/4G - has made the old singles chart obsolete! We live in ever-changing times! We have to accept streaming is now the standard measurement of chart success. I guess the OCC will continue to tweak the format to make it as fair as possible.

        Ups:
        Dancing On My Own drops out the top 40. ABOUT TIME!
        After the Afterparty is out of the top 40. I feared that would be in for quite a few more weeks but no! Nice surprise.
        Human climbs. I actually rather like that song, especially the Rudimental remix.
        Where is This Town going? Good, it's terrible.
        The amount of songs taking big drops. Yes it happened to some good songs like Let Me Love You but at least there's a little more movement.
        Two new entries high in the top 5, not heard either yet but you know, movement.

        Downs:
        Rockabye is number 1 YET AGAIN. It's technically a good thing it's passed 7 Years but just as there looked to be a shorter number 1 tenure, BAM, it gets ruined by, and this is the last time I will call them this as it's getting excessive, a sellout group.
        Only FOUR climbers within the top 40... and the BIGGEST was Zara Larson's crappy new song. I explained last week why I don't like it, so I'm not gonna repeat myself.
        Driving Home for Christmas has reentered but not Do They Know It's Christmas. Hahahaha! Well you could say it's coz everyone's already bought the latter but that doesn't mean anything in the dark age of streaming.
        Treat You Better drops out... oh well, it was gonna eventually.

        And finally, Talk by Little Mix enters. In all honesty, it's actually an okay song. It's got a nice dance beat and the lyrics aren't extremely generic for a song titled 'Touch'.

        "Rockabye" by Clean Bandit (feat Anne-Marie and Sean Paul) remains at number 1 for a sixth straight week.

        "Just Hold On" by Steve Aoki and Louis Tomlinson has debuted at number 2. The song was released on December 10, 2016 and was written by Louis Tomlinson, Steve Aoki, Eric Rosse, Sasha Sloan and Sir Nolan. It was produced by Steve Aoki, Sir Nolan and Jay Pryor. I really like this song. I hope it reaches number 1 in England. It's already number 1 in New Zealand and Scotland. Louis Tomlinson's birthday is on Christmas Eve. How cool would it be if the song was this year's Christmas number 1 in the UK?

        "I Don't Wanna Live Forever" by Zayn & Taylor Swift debuts at number 16.         Yes, I agree. In the US, in addition to the Hot 100 Singles chart, there are also the Digital Songs Sales, Streaming Songs and Radio Songs (they take that into account which I'm surprised they don't in the UK), the three component charts that get blended into the Singles chart. That way, it is possible to determine, relatively speaking, what is causing a song to have success in a particular week.

        Unfortunately, for the Official Singles chart it is impossible to do so due to the use term "combined sales" in the weekly chart highlights article. I don't think they even cite the actual sales nor actual streaming numbers most of the time. One thing that's probably good that's happening next year is the change to increase the number of streams to get an equivalent sale from 1000 to 1500 which hopefully will result in less stagnant charts.

        Well the Christmas #1 of 2009 was one of the most interesting & shocking charts of all-time in the UK...
        So the winner of the X Factor that year was Joe McElderry (a one-hit wonder in the UK) & his song was a cover of Miley Cyrus' 'The Climb'. It was predicted to be the Christmas #1 that year, but that would be the fourth consecutive year X Factor had got the Christmas #1. So a family set up an online campaign to change that & give another song a chance. The song they chose was Rage Against The Machine's 1991 hit 'Killing In The Name'. It actually worked when they got 500k signatures & 'Killing In The Name' actually got to #1! :D LOL
